@Node "NODE_INTRO" "Skully.guide/NODE_INTRO"
@Next "NODE_LICENSE"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}What is this stuff ?@{ub}

 France Telecom's been settling demo sites for ADSL since 1998. Basically
ADSL is a means to use your copper phone line to transmit data with high
bandwidth up to (10Mb/s).

At the beginning of their experimentations, FT provided 'normal' dhcp
connections to their customers, and the only stuff that was needed for
them to be able to connect the internet using an ADSL line was a stack
able to manage DHCP. Miami is such a stack.

 Alas, the DHCP-only solution was not retained by France Telecom who wanted 
a means to authenticate the user behind the wire. The current solution
involves a different architecture DANA (for Data Application Network Adapter),
that relies on a QNX frontend who, from the user point of view handles
the establishment of the connection, and the dhcp leases. 
DANA is described at http://www.alcatel.com/telecom/asd/keytech/adsl/dana.


So the connection to the internet behaves like this:
1) your tcp/ip stack retrieves an address dynamically allocated by the Dana
   server.

2) You're then connected with the dana server, but unable to reach anything
   else. To 'open the door' you've got to autenticate (and keep the door open).
   It's possible to do that using a telnet session and an http post to
   the dana server containing your login/passwd/provider, or to use the 
   RAS applicative protocol to do it automatically. 
   Currently, I know only three programs able to use this RAS protocol.

   RASManager/RAS1218 on Windows 9x/NT
   Winner and Loser on Linux are posix programs that can be recompiled on any
   platform
   Skully on the Amiga.

@{b}Do I need this ?@{ub}

Well... you need it if you have an amiga, an adsl line and a provider 
who uses dana for the connection establishment. The two I heard of up to
now are France Telecom (in guess where ? yes: France ) and TurboLine in
Belgium. I had contacts with a guy from Alcatel based in Canada who
chat a bit about this protocol with me, but I'm not sure it is used
there.

@{b}Ok I need a Dana client, what do I need else ? @{ub}

Short: an amiga, an ethernet card, wires etc... , miamidx, and skully.

To be able to use your dana connection with your amiga you need
an AMItcp compliant TCP/Ip stack that is able to manage Dana servers' DHCP.
Today ( August 1999 ) there is only one that does the trick, it's Miaa miDx
from nordicglobal. Miami 3.2b and previous manage to get the address from
the server, but the connection is cut 5 minutes later. 

MiamiDx is not supposed to handle DHCP better than Miami. But believe me,
intentionnaly or not, it does.

MUI is required to use skully.  I dunna which version, but it's should work
with MUI 3.8.

You will also need the adress of the Dana server (can easily be found,
it's the only host that you're able to reach), a login and a password,
given to you by your provider.


@EndNode

