Skully is FREEWARE.

It means you don't have to pay anything to get it. 
If someone sells you Skully, you've been faked. It will always be freeware. 

Unlike the previous (confidential) release, Skully is not crippled in
any way. If you've got a crippled version of Skully that timeouts
and hanghup after a few minutes, it's probably not an official one,
and you should download the latest available release from aminet.

These crippled releases are test snapshots that I don't want to be spreaded. 
Official ones are not limited in any thing (at least not intentionally :).

Anyway if you find skully useful, I would apreciate a little mail of support.
Just mail me at philippe.torrelli@wanadoo.fr. You're in no way forced to
do it, but it's your interest cause it could help me to make skully a better
software.

Any bug report, feature suggestion, or question will be answered.
Even if it's ok for you and does what you want, please send a me an email,
I'd like to have a base of contacts to be able to improve skully, provide
default configurations, or be able to test against new versions of the
protocol.

 I'd like to have contacts with people using it from belgium,
cause I've no clue if skully works with Turboline (probably not :( ),
and 'd like to fix it if it doesn't.

I don't expect a very  big feedback, Amiga users being quite seldom
here in France - and ADSL not as widespread as V90, so any feedback 
is useful.

For the rest:

This program is not guaranteed in any way, use only at your own risk. 
I cannot be held responsible for any usage, damage, or trouble of any
sort that could be caused by Skully. If you don't agree with it, just
don't run it. 

If something in the developpement of skully ripes any copyright law,
let me know, I'll try to do my best to correct that.

You can pass Skully to someone else, distribute it, copy it but you're not
allowed to alterate it, neither in it's integrity (all the files must
be present) nor in its form. If you patch it, either contact me so that
I integrate your patches in the next version, or keep it on your drive.

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_INST" "Skully.guide/NODE_INST"
@Next "NODE_SETTINGS"
@Prev "NODE_LICENSE"
@Toc "Main"

Just copy the Skully drawer wherever you want,  or the skully
program in WbStartup. Make sure it is run after MiamiDx is loaded and
connected if you want to auto online.
Skully can be run from shell as well as from workbench, so feel free
to run it from whereever you like.

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_SETTINGS" "Skully.guide/NODE_SETTINGS"
@Next "NODE_BUGS"
@Prev "NODE_INST"
@Toc "Main"

The setup of Skully is quite straightforward.

UserId:
 This your user Id without the ending /fti.

Password:
 The password that your provider gave you.

Dana Address:
 The Ip address of your provider.

Src Port:
 The source UDP port used to call the Dana server. Usually 5555.

Dest Port:
 The destination port of the Dana server. Usually 5555.

Auto Online:
 If checked, skully will connect you to the internet when run.
 Miami Dx should be online if you want it to work.

HideGui:
 If checked, skully will start iconified.

Timeout:
 Timeout used to retransmit packets that were not acknowledged by
 the server. If the value is high, skully can take long time to
 disconnect in case the line is down, or miami is offline.

Turboline:
 Not yet implemented.

@EndNode

@Node "NODE_BUGS" "Skully.guide/NODE_BUGS"
@Next "NODE_HISTORY"
@Prev "NODE_SETTINGS"
@Toc "Main"


			Known Bugs


* LONG READ Hit after alerts when skully is online. 
  Seems related to  Net Events .
  (too many,retransmission, demo timeout, unexpected pack..)

* Sometimes after a crash of your machine or a reboot, skully will
  be disconnected after more or less 5 minutes. It's not a bug. 
  In such case, just off/on your TCP stack, and reconnect skully. 
  A workaround for this problem will be implemented in a future version.

@EndNode

